int main() {
    std::ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    std::cin.tie(NULL);
    int t;
    std::cin >> t;
    while (t--) {
        int n;
        std::cin >> n;
        std::vector<long long> a(2 * n);
        for (int i = 0; i < 2 * n; ++i) {
            std::cin >> a[i];
        }
        std::sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        // The problem asks for the minimum absolute difference between medians.
        // Let the sorted skill levels be a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        // If we partition the students into two classes, each with an odd number of students,
        // the smallest possible median for one class is a_0 (if it has 1 student).
        // The largest possible median for one class is a_{2n-1} (if it has 1 student).
        //
        // Consider the case where one class has k students and the other has 2n-k students.
        // Both k and 2n-k must be odd. This means k must be odd.
        //
        // The key insight is that to minimize the difference between medians,
        // we should try to make the medians as close as possible.
        //
        // If we sort all 2n students, the median of the first class will be some a_i
        // and the median of the second class will be some a_j.
        //
        // The minimum possible difference is achieved when the two medians are
        // a_{n-1} and a_n.
        //
        // To see this, consider the sorted array a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        // If we pick a_i as the median of the first class, and a_j as the median of the second class.
        //
        // For a_i to be a median of a class of size 2k+1, there must be k elements <= a_i
        // and k elements >= a_i in that class.
        //
        // The optimal strategy is to take the n smallest elements for one class and the n largest elements for the other class.
        // This is not quite right because class sizes must be odd.
        //
        // The problem is equivalent to finding two indices i and j such that
        // a_i is the median of one class and a_j is the median of the other,
        // and |a_i - a_j| is minimized.
        //
        // The crucial observation is that if we sort all students, the median of the first class
        // will be a_i and the median of the second class will be a_j.
        // To minimize |a_i - a_j|, we want i and j to be as close as possible.
        //
        // The smallest possible median for any class is a_0 (class size 1).
        // The largest possible median for any class is a_{2n-1} (class size 1).
        //
        // Consider the two "middle" elements in the sorted array: a_{n-1} and a_n.
        // Can we always form two classes such that their medians are a_{n-1} and a_n?
        //
        // Let's try to make a_{n-1} the median of one class and a_n the median of the other.
        //
        // Class 1: median a_{n-1}.
        // To make a_{n-1} the median, we need to pick some elements.
        // We can pick a_0, a_1, ..., a_{n-1} for the first class. This class has n students.
        // If n is odd, then a_{(n-1)/2} would be its median. This is not a_{n-1}.
        //
        // The problem is simpler than trying to construct the classes.
        // The minimum possible difference between medians will always be between a_{n-1} and a_n.
        //
        // Why?
        // Suppose we have two classes, C1 and C2, with medians M1 and M2 respectively.
        // Let M1 <= M2.
        //
        // C1 has size 2k1+1. M1 is the (k1+1)-th element.
        // C2 has size 2k2+1. M2 is the (k2+1)-th element.
        // Total students: (2k1+1) + (2k2+1) = 2n.
        // So 2k1 + 2k2 + 2 = 2n => k1 + k2 + 1 = n.
        //
        // In the sorted full array `a`:
        // M1 must be at least `a_{k1}` (because there are k1 elements smaller than or equal to M1 in C1, and these must come from `a_0` to `a_{k1}`).
        // M2 must be at most `a_{2n - 1 - k2}` (because there are k2 elements larger than or equal to M2 in C2, and these must come from `a_{2n-1-k2}` to `a_{2n-1}`).
        //
        // Also, M1 and M2 must be distinct elements from the original array `a`.
        //
        // Consider the elements `a_0, ..., a_{n-1}` and `a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}`.
        //
        // The median of a class of size $2k+1$ is the $(k+1)$-th element.
        // This means there are $k$ elements less than or equal to it, and $k$ elements greater than or equal to it.
        //
        // Let the two medians be $m_1$ and $m_2$. Assume $m_1 \le m_2$.
        //
        // For $m_1$ to be a median of a class of size $2k_1+1$, there must be at least $k_1$ elements in that class that are $\le m_1$.
        // For $m_2$ to be a median of a class of size $2k_2+1$, there must be at least $k_2$ elements in that class that are $\ge m_2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements less than or equal to $m_1$ in the entire set of $2n$ students is at least $k_1+1$.
        // The total number of elements greater than or equal to $m_2$ in the entire set of $2n$ students is at least $k_2+1$.
        //
        // The elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ are the first $n$ elements.
        // The elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are the last $n$ elements.
        //
        // The median of the first class, $m_1$, must be one of $a_0, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // The median of the second class, $m_2$, must be one of $a_0, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        //
        // The smallest possible value for $m_2$ is $a_n$.
        // To show this: $m_2$ is the $(k_2+1)$-th element of its class.
        // There are $k_2$ elements in its class that are $\ge m_2$.
        // The total number of elements in the array that are $\ge m_2$ must be at least $k_2+1$.
        // The total number of elements in the array that are $\le m_2$ must be at least $2n - k_2$.
        //
        // We know $k_1 + k_2 + 1 = n$.
        // So $k_2 = n - k_1 - 1$.
        //
        // The number of elements in the sorted array $a$ that are $\ge m_2$ is $2n - (\text{index of } m_2)$.
        // This must be at least $k_2+1$.
        // So $2n - (\text{index of } m_2) \ge n - k_1 - 1 + 1 = n - k_1$.
        //
        // The number of elements in the sorted array $a$ that are $\le m_1$ is $(\text{index of } m_1) + 1$.
        // This must be at least $k_1+1$.
        // So $(\text{index of } m_1) + 1 \ge k_1+1 \implies (\text{index of } m_1) \ge k_1$.
        //
        // This means $m_1 \ge a_{k_1}$.
        //
        // Also, $m_2$ must be at least $a_{n-k_1-1}$.
        //
        // The minimum possible value for $m_2$ is $a_n$.
        // The maximum possible value for $m_1$ is $a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // Consider the elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ and $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        //
        // If we pick $a_{n-1}$ as the median of the first class, and $a_n$ as the median of the second class.
        // Can we always construct such classes?
        //
        // Yes.
        // Class 1: Take $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{n-1}$. This class has $n$ students.
        // If $n$ is odd, its median is $a_{(n-1)/2}$.
        // If $n$ is even, this is not a valid class size.
        //
        // The problem states that each class must have an odd number of students.
        //
        // The crucial observation is that the minimum difference will always be between $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$.
        //
